oved Duplicate Rows: Checked for duplicate rows using duplicated().\n","If duplicates were found, they were dropped using drop_duplicates().\n","\n","Handled Missing Values: Identified columns with missing values using isnull().sum().\n","For numerical columns, I filled missing values with the median (e.g., price, reviews_per_month).\n","For categorical columns, I filled missing values with the mode (e.g., neighbourhood_group, neighbourhood).\n","\n","Checked and Converted Data Types: Ensured that columns like price are numeric, and last_review is in the datetime format.\n","Any columns that had the wrong data type were converted appropriately (e.g., price to numeric).\n","\n","Encoded Categorical Variables: Applied One-Hot Encoding to categorical variables like neighbourhood, room_type, and neighbourhood_group. This method creates new binary columns for each category.\n","If there were ordinal columns, I could apply Label Encoding, but no specific examples of ordinal data were provided in the dataset.\n","\n","Handled Outliers: Used the Interquartile Range (IQR) method to detect and remove outliers in the price column. This helps in making sure that extreme outliers don't distort statistical analysis and models.\n","\n","Feature Engineering: Extracted year, month, and day from the last_review column to create new features such as review_year, review_month, and review_day. These features can be useful for trend analysis over time.\n","Removed the last_review column if it was no longer necessary after creating these new features.\n","\n","Final Check on the Dataset: After making the changes, I performed a final check on the dataset, including displaying the cleaned data (head()), checking summary statistics (describe()), and reviewing the shape of the cleaned dataset.\n","\n","\n","Insights and Observations:\n","\n","Missing Data: Several columns had missing data, particularly reviews_per_month, neighbourhood_group, and neighbourhood. After imputing these missing values using the median for numerical columns and the mode for categorical columns, the dataset became complete, and no missing values remained.\n","\n","Data Types: After data type corrections, it was ensured that columns like price were numeric, last_review was datetime, and categorical variables were treated as objects.\n","The conversion of last_review to datetime allowed us to extract useful features like review_year, review_month, and review_day.\n","\n","Handling Outliers: Outliers in the price column were identified using the IQR method and removed. This ensures that extreme values (e.g., extremely high-priced listings) do not distort the results when performing analysis.\n","\n","Feature Engineering: Creating features such as review_year, review_month, and review_day from the last_review column allows you to perform time-based analysis, such as analyzing trends in reviews over time, and seasonality in the number of listings and reviews.\n","\n","Categorical Variables: One-Hot Encoding was applied to columns like neighbourhood, room_type, and neighbourhood_group. This allows categorical variables to be represented as binary features, making them suitable for machine learning algorithms.\n","\n","Data Summary and Shape: After cleaning, the shape of the dataset was checked. The dataset size may have reduced due to the removal of duplicates and outliers, but the data should now be in a much cleaner state for analysis."],"metadata":{"id":"LbyXE7I1olp8"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## ***4. Data Vizualization, Storytelling & Experimenting with charts : Understand the relationships between variables***"],"metadata":{"id":"GF8Ens_Soomf"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["   **(1) Distribution Of Airbnb Bookings Price Range Using Histogram**\n"],"metadata":{"id":"0wOQAZs5pc--"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Create a figure with a custom size\n","plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))\n","\n","# Set the seaborn theme to darkgrid\n","sns.set_theme(style='darkgrid')\n","\n","# Create a histogram of the 'price' column of the Airbnb_df dataframe\n","# using sns distplot function and specifying the color as red\n","sns.distplot(Airbnb_df['price'],color=('r'))\n","\n","# Add labels to the x-axis and y-axis\n","plt.xlabel('Price', fontsize=14)\n","plt.ylabel('Density', fontsize=14)\n","\n","# Add a title to the plot\n","plt.title('Distribution of Airbnb Prices',fontsize=15)\n"],"metadata":{"id":"7v_ESjsspbW7"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["##### 1. Why did you pick the specific chart?"],"metadata":{"id":"K5QZ13OEpz2H"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["\n","\n","1. A histogram is particularly useful for understanding how a dataset is distributed across different value ranges. For example, when you plot the distribution of Airbnb prices, you can see whether most listings fall within a particular price range or if there are some extreme outliers.\n","It shows the frequency of observations (in this case, Airbnb listings) falling within specific price intervals (bins). This helps you understand the concentration of prices in different ranges.\n","Identifying Skewness:\n","\n","2. Histograms help identify the shape of the distribution. For Airbnb prices, you might notice that most listings are priced low, but there are a few very expensive listings that could create a positive skew (long tail on the right). This skew is important to know because it indicates that while most listings are affordable, there are some outliers with significantly higher prices.\n","Without a histogram, it would be harder to visually assess this skewness.\n","Detecting Outliers:\n","\n","3. Outliers are extreme values that fall outside the expected range. A histogram helps detect these outliers by showing whether there are a significant number of listings priced much higher (or lower) than the majority of listings.\n","For example, if most Airbnb prices are concentrated between $50 and $200, but there are a few listings priced at $1,000 or more, the histogram will visually display this anomaly.\n","Understanding Patterns and Trends:\n","\n","4. The histogram allows you to identify patterns in pricing. For example, if you’re analyzing Airbnb pricing across New York City, the histogram might show that certain price ranges (e.g., $100-$150) are more common for listings, and this could be an indication of what most travelers are willing to pay or what hosts typically charge.\n","By visually representing these patterns, you can gain valuable insights into the price distribution."],"metadata":{"id":"XESiWehPqBRc"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["##### 2. What is/are the insight(s) found from the chart?"],"metadata":{"id":"lQ7QKXXCp7Bj"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["1. Skewness in Pricing: The distribution of Airbnb prices is likely to be positively skewed, meaning that while most listings are priced lower, there are a few high-priced outliers. This suggests that a significant portion of Airbnb listings in New York City are affordable, but there are also luxury listings or unique properties with much higher prices. The long tail on the right side of the histogram would confirm this, indicating that there are some expensive outliers driving up the overall price range.\n","\n","2. Concentration of Listings in Certain Price Ranges: From the histogram, it’s easy to see that a majority of Airbnb listings fall within a specific price range, often between $50 and $200. This suggests that most travelers are likely booking budget to mid-range options, and these listings are more common than high-end or extremely cheap ones.\n","\n","3.Presence of Outliers: The histogram would also reveal that a small percentage of listings have extremely high prices, which may indicate rare, high-demand properties such as luxury apartments, penthouses, or entire houses. These high-priced outliers are likely not representative of the general pricing trend, and they might skew the perception of the average price of Airbnb listings.\n","\n","4. Overall Price Trends: The histogram can provide a quick overview of the general pricing trend for Airbnb in New York City. It shows if most listings are clustered around lower prices, suggesting affordability, or if they are more expensive on average, giving an indication of the market's competitiveness and demand."],"metadata":{"id":"C_j1G7yiqdRP"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["##### 3. Will the gained insights help creating a positive business impact?\n","Are there any insights that lead to negative growth? Justify with specific reason."],"metadata":{"id":"448CDAPjqfQr"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Yes, the insights gained from the histogram of Airbnb prices can significantly contribute to creating a positive business impact, while also helping identify areas that may lead to negative growth if not addressed properly.\n","\n","Positive Business Impact:\n","Targeting the Right Market Segment: The histogram shows that most Airbnb listings are concentrated within a mid-range price (e.g., $50-$200). This insight helps Airbnb hosts and businesses understand where the majority of demand lies. Hosts can adjust their pricing strategies to cater to the most lucrative market segment—budget to mid-range travelers—thereby attracting more guests and maximizing occupancy rates.\n","Additionally, businesses can develop marketing campaigns that emphasize affordability for budget-conscious travelers, leading to increased bookings for hosts with competitive pricing.\n","\n","Identifying Opportunities for Premium Offerings: Although the majority of listings are in the lower price ranges, the outliers (high-priced listings) indicate a market for luxury or unique properties. This can help businesses or hosts identify niche opportunities, such as luxury experiences or premium properties. For example, if a host offers a high-end property or experience, they can tailor marketing and pricing strategies for the premium segment and generate higher revenue.\n","Understanding this, hosts can ensure they’re offering something distinct to cater to guests who seek luxury or unique stays, leading to higher revenue per booking.\n","\n","Price Optimization and Competitive Advantage: The insight about the distribution of prices enables businesses and hosts to optimize their pricing by understanding where most competitors’ prices fall and where gaps exist in the market. By adjusting prices to align with demand patterns, hosts can maximize revenue and maintain competitiveness, leading to a higher return on investment (ROI).\n","Identifying Potential Partnerships or Expansions:\n","\n","If certain neighborhoods or price ranges are found to be more popular, businesses can consider expanding their listings in those areas. It allows Airbnb to build partnerships with hosts or businesses located in neighborhoods with high demand, fostering community engagement and contributing to business growth.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"3cspy4FjqxJW"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["#### Chart - 2"],"metadata":{"id":"KSlN3yHqYklG"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Chart - 2 Total Listing/Property count in Each Neighborhood Group using Count plot\n","# Count the number of listings in each neighborhood group and store the result in a Pandas series\n","counts = Airbnb_df['neighbourhood_group'].value_counts()\n","\n","# Reset the index of the series so that the neighborhood groups become columns in the resulting dataframe\n","Top_Neighborhood_group = counts.reset_index()\n","\n","# Rename the columns of the dataframe to be more descriptive\n","Top_Neighborhood_group.columns = ['Neighborhood_Groups', 'Listing_Counts']\n","\n","# display the resulting DataFrame\n","Top_Neighborhood_group\n"],"metadata":{"id":"R4YgtaqtYklH"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Set the figure size\n","plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\n","\n","# Create a countplot of the neighbourhood group data\n","sns.countplot(Airbnb_df['