 where top-performing neighborhoods are and also highlight lesser-performing groups based on review volume.\n","Reason: A pie chart uses visual slices to represent data, making it effective for showcasing the dominance of certain groups, especially when the goal is to understand the overall contribution of each group in a simple way.\n","Simplicity and Accessibility:\n","\n","Pie charts are easier to interpret for a wide audience, especially when the goal is to convey proportions or relative significance. Instead of dealing with numerical data or bar height comparisons, the pie chart's slices directly provide an immediate sense of how each neighborhood group compares.\n","Reason: In business or reports where a quick snapshot of data is needed, pie charts are accessible, requiring minimal interpretation from the viewer. The percentage labels (autopct='%1.1f%%') add clarity and make it easy to understand the exact share of each neighborhood group.\n","Visually Appealing Representation:\n","\n","The use of a pie chart helps make the data visually engaging, particularly when dealing with relatively simple categorical data like neighborhood groups. Instead of using a bar chart or line graph, a pie chart is a clean and straightforward way to represent categorical distributions, which is particularly useful in this case since we are summarizing maximum values for groups.\n","Emphasis on Comparative View:\n","\n","Since we are looking at the maximum number of reviews in each neighborhood group, the pie chart emphasizes how the neighborhoods compare in terms of their best performance. It can quickly highlight if any single neighborhood group outshines others in terms of reviews.\n","Reason: By representing maximum values, the pie chart draws attention to which neighborhoods consistently gather the most reviews, suggesting a higher level of engagement or popularity in those areas."],"metadata":{"id":"8agQvks0phqQ"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["##### 2. What is/are the 